04468nam a22006015i 9786155211546DE-B159720230103011142.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230103t20082008hu     fo  d z      eng d  a9786155211546  a(DE-B1597)633206  a(OCoLC)1338019104  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahucHU 7aBIO0180002bisacsh1 aByford, Jovan, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDenial and Repression of Anti-Semitism :bPost-Communist Rehabilitation of the Serbian Bishop Nikolaj Velimirovic /cJovan Byford. 1aBudapest ;aNew York : bCentral European University Press, c[2008] 4c©2008  a1 online resource (288 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. I ntroduction -- t2. The Life of Nikolaj Velimirović and His Changing Public Image, 1945–2003 -- t3. Collective Remembering and Collective Forgetting: Memory of Nikolaj Velimirović and the Repression of Controversy -- t4. From Repression to Denial: Responses of the Serbian Orthodox Church to Accusations of Antisemitism -- t5. “He was merely quoting the Bible!”: Denial of Velimirović’s Antisemitism -- t6. Antisemitism as Prophecy: Social Construction of Velimirović’s Sanctity -- t7. Conclusion -- tReferences -- tIndex -- tIllustrations0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBishop Nikolaj Velimirović (1881–1956) is arguably one the most controversial figures in contemporary Serbian national culture. Having been vilified by the former Yugoslav Communist authorities as a fascist and an antisemite, this Orthodox Christian thinker has over the past two decades come to be regarded in Serbian society as the most important religious person since medieval times and an embodiment of the authentic Serbian national spirit. Velimirović was formally canonised by the Serbian Orthodox Church in 2003. In this book, Jovan Byford charts the posthumous transformation of Velimirović from 'traitor' to 'saint' and examines the dynamics of repression and denial that were used to divert public attention from the controversies surrounding the bishop's life, the most important of which is his antisemitism. Byford offers the first detailed examination of the way in which an Eastern Orthodox Church manages controversy surrounding the presence of antisemitism within its ranks and he considers the implications of the continuing reverence of Nikolaj Velimirović for the persistence of antisemitism in Serbian Orthodox culture and in Serbian society as a whole. This book is based on a detailed examination of the changing representation of Bishop Nikolaj Velimirović in the Serbian media and in commemorative discourse devoted to him. The book also makes extensive use of exclusive interviews with a number of Serbian public figures who have been actively involved in the bishop’s rehabilitation over the past two decades.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 03. Jan 2023) 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Religious.2bisacsh  a20th century, Biography, Media, Memory politics, Orthodox Church, Saints, Serbia.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCentral European University Press eBook-Package 2013-1998z978311078055040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9786155211546423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9786155211546/original  a978-3-11-078055-0  Central European University Press eBook-Package 2013-1998c1998d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK